==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Puritan
<hw>Pu"ri*tan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
<er>Purity</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One
who, in the time of Queen Elizabeth and the first two Stuarts, opposed
traditional and formal usages, and advocated simpler forms of faith and
worship than those established by law; -- originally, a term of
reproach. The Puritans formed the bulk of the early population of New
England.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The <xex>Puritans</xex> were afterward distinguished as
<xex>Political Puritans</xex>, <xex>Doctrinal Puritans</xex>, and
<xex>Puritans in Discipline</xex>.</note> <rj><au>Hume.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who is scrupulous and strict in his religious
life; -- often used reproachfully or in contempt; one who has overstrict
notions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She would make a <qex>puritan</qex> of the devil.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Puritan</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Puritan
<hw>Pu"ri*tan</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Puritans;
resembling, or characteristic of, the Puritans.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Puritanical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Puritanic</ent>⟦br⟧
